pgTitle: List of members of the parliament of Croatia, 2008–11

tableData.tdHtmlString: Dragutin Lesar (HNS) resigns from the Croatian People's Party, reducing them to six seats.
tableData.text: Dragutin Lesar (HNS) resigns from the Croatian People's Party , reducing them to six seats.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Zlatko Horvat (HNS), who since January 2008 held the seat of Radimir Čačić, county prefect of Varaždin County, is expelled from the Croatian People's Party for entering the May 2009 local elections in the city of Varaždin as an independent. This reduced HNS to five seats.
tableData.text: Zlatko Horvat (HNS), who since January 2008 held the seat of Radimir Čačić , county prefect of Varaždin County , is expelled from the Croatian People's Party for entering the May 2009 local elections in the city of Varaždin as an independent. This reduced HNS to five seats.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Ivica Pančić (SDP) resigns from the Social Democratic Party, reducing them to 55 seats.
tableData.text: Ivica Pančić (SDP) resigns from the Social Democratic Party , reducing them to 55 seats.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Dragutin Lesar (Ind.) establishes the centre-left Croatian Labourists (HL) and becomes their only member of parliament.
tableData.text: Dragutin Lesar (Ind.) establishes the centre-left Croatian Labourists (HL) and becomes their only member of parliament.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Ivan Čehok (HSLS) resigns from the Croatian Social Liberal Party following the party's exit from the ruling coalition, reducing them to a single seat.
tableData.text: Ivan Čehok (HSLS) resigns from the Croatian Social Liberal Party following the party's exit from the ruling coalition, reducing them to a single seat.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Ivica Pančić (Ind.) joins the non-parliamentary centre-left party Croatian Social Democrats (HSD), becoming their only member of parliament.
tableData.text: Ivica Pančić (Ind.) joins the non-parliamentary centre-left party Croatian Social Democrats (HSD), becoming their only member of parliament.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Zoran Vinković (SDP) resigns from the Social Democratic Party of Croatia, reducing them to 54 seats.
tableData.text: Zoran Vinković (SDP) resigns from the Social Democratic Party of Croatia, reducing them to 54 seats.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Đurđa Adlešič (HSLS) returns to parliament after stepping down from the post of deputy prime minister in the Cabinet of Jadranka Kosor following Croatian Social Liberal Party's decision to leave the ruling coalition in July 2010. She takes the seat as an independent, having resigned from the party in the meantime, leaving HSLS with no representation in parliament.
tableData.text: Đurđa Adlešič (HSLS) returns to parliament after stepping down from the post of deputy prime minister in the Cabinet of Jadranka Kosor following Croatian Social Liberal Party's decision to leave the ruling coalition in July 2010. She takes the seat as an independent, having resigned from the party in the meantime, leaving HSLS with no representation in parliament.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Former prime minister Ivo Sanader (HDZ) returns to parliament, having resigned from the post in July 2009 and after being expelled from the Croatian Democratic Union in January 2010. He takes the seat as an independent, reducing Croatian Democratic Union to 65 seats.
tableData.text: Former prime minister Ivo Sanader (HDZ) returns to parliament, having resigned from the post in July 2009 and after being expelled from the Croatian Democratic Union in January 2010. He takes the seat as an independent, reducing Croatian Democratic Union to 65 seats.

tableData.tdHtmlString: Zoran Vinković (Ind.) joins the right-wing regionalist Croatian Democratic Alliance of Slavonia and Baranja (HDSSB) as their fourth member of parliament.
tableData.text: Zoran Vinković (Ind.) joins the right-wing regionalist Croatian Democratic Alliance of Slavonia and Baranja (HDSSB) as their fourth member of parliament.
